  "created": "2025-10-15",
  "description": "DNA Mismatch Repair (MMR) in E. coli corrects replication errors including base-base mismatches and insertion-deletion loops (IDLs). The MutS protein recognizes mismatches, MutL coordinates the response, and MutH endonuclease creates a strand break at a hemimethylated GATC site to direct repair to the newly synthesized (unmethylated) strand. Exonucleases then degrade from the nick toward and past the mismatch, DNA polymerase III resynthesizes the excised region, and DNA ligase seals the remaining nick. The system increases replication fidelity ~1000-fold and is highly conserved across all life. This flowchart illustrates the complete MMR pathway from mismatch recognition through strand-specific correction, including the critical strand discrimination mechanism.",
  "id": "ecoli_mismatch_repair",
  "keywords": [
    "mismatch repair",
    "mmr",
    "muts",
    "mutl",
    "muth",
    "dam methylation",
    "replication fidelity",
    "strand discrimination",
    "gatc",
    "exonucleases"
  ],
